en: On my way home from work, I detoured through the park, which I never did, but the weather was perfect. And I was wearing a floppy-brimmed hat, which I never had, but Mom mailed it to me the week before, and I felt like I owed it to her to at least try it out. I was reading as I walked—which I’d vowed to stop doing because I’d nearly caused a bike accident doing so weeks earlier—when suddenly, a warm breeze caught the hat’s brim. It lifted off my head and swooped over an azalea bush. Right to a tall, handsome blond man’s feet.

en: He walked me to the couch and sat me down. Then, as far as I could figure, a couple of tectonic plates must have smashed together, because the whole world lurched, and my ears started ringing so loudly I could only catch bits of what he was saying. None of it could be right. It didn’t make sense.

en: Still, a chorus of ridiculous little voices rises as I approach, cries of “Miss Daffy!” and other adorable mispronunciations of my name. In my heart, it feels like little kernels are bursting into fluffy blossoms of popcorn.
st: Leha ho le joalo, chorus ea mantsoe a manyane a sa utloahaleng a phahama ha ke ntse ke atamela, ke lla ka "Miss Daffy!" le lipolelo tse ling tse ntle tsa lebitso la ka. Ka pelong ea ka, e ikutloa eka li-kernels tse nyane li phatloha ka har'a li-fluffy blossoms tsa popcorn.
yo: Síbẹ̀síbẹ̀, ọ̀pọ̀lọpọ̀ àwọn ohùn kékeré ẹlẹ́rìndòdò ń gòkè bí mo ṣe ń súnmọ́, igbe "Omidan Daffy!" àti àwọn àṣìṣe orúkọ mi mìíràn tó rẹwà. Nínú ọkàn mi, ó dàbí ẹni pé àwọn èkùrọ́ kékeré ń fọ́ sínú òdòdó popcorn tó rọ̀.
tn: Le fa go ntse jalo, go na le modumo o o sa tlwaelegang o o buang ka ga me, fa ke ntse ke atamela, ke lela ka "Miss Daffy!" le dilo tse dingwe tse di sa tlwaelegang tsa leina la me. Mo pelong ya me, go lebega go na le disedi tse di nnye tse di falang mo di-popcorn.

en: He flinches. I’m not sure at which part, but something I said definitely shifted his mood a bit. “They’re also rich,” he says. “Ninety dollars is nothing to them, and at least this way, they have to spend the next few months worrying that we’ll show up and ruin their big day.”
st: O ile a inka intshi. Ha ke na bonnete ba hore na ke karolo efe, empa ho na le ntho eo ke e buileng ka sebele e ile ea fetola maikutlo a hae hanyane. "Barui le bona ba ruile," a rialo. "Liranta tse robong ha se letho ho tsona, 'me bonyane ka tsela ena, ba tlameha ho qeta likhoeli tse' maloa tse latelang ba tšoenyehile hore re tla bonts'a le ho senya letsatsi la bona le leholo."

en: A smell like burning cedar wafts toward us as we enter the dimly lit room. A sleek modern bar runs along the left wall, the wall behind it entirely smoked glass, massive wine casks stacked behind it and softly glowing in golden light. The other three walls are likewise glass, but these look out over the vineyards, a narrow wooden counter mounted along them so people can watch the sunset while they sip. High-tops are arranged in the middle of the room, and in the windowed wall opposite the bar, a huge slate fireplace reaches toward the vaulted ceiling, flames crackling and leaping within it.
st: Monko o kang o tukang kedare e tukang ka nģ'a rōna ha re kena ka kamoreng e khanyang. Bar e boreleli ea sejoale-joale e matha hammoho le leboteng le letšehali, lebota le ka mor'a lona le tsuba ka ho feletseng khalase, li-casks tsa veine tse kholo li stacked ka mor'a eona 'me li khanya ka bonolo ka khanya ea khauta. Marako a mang a mararo a tšoana le khalase, empa tsena li shebile holim'a lirapa tsa morara, khaontara ea lehong e moqotetsane e mounted hammoho le batho ba ka shebella letsatsi ha letsatsi le likela ha ba ntse ba sip. Litlhōrō tse phahameng li hlophisitsoe bohareng ba kamore, 'me lerakong le ka fensetereng le fapaneng le bareng, mollo o moholo oa mollo o fihlang holim'a siling e vaulted, malakabe a petsoha le ho tlola ka hare ho eona.
yo: Òórùn bíi igi kedari tí ó ń jó máa ń lọ sí ọ̀dọ̀ wa bí a ṣe ń wọ inú yàrá tí iná rẹ̀ kò mọ́lẹ̀. Ilé-ọtí ìgbàlódé tó rẹwà ń ṣiṣẹ́ lẹ́gbẹ̀ẹ́ ògiri òsì, ògiri tí ó wà lẹ́yìn rẹ̀ gíláàsì èéfín pátápátá, àwọn àpótí ọtí wáìnì ńlá tí wọ́n kó jọ lẹ́yìn rẹ̀ tí ó sì ń tàn díẹ̀díẹ̀ nínú iná wúrà. Àwọn ògiri mẹ́tẹ̀ẹ̀ta yòókù náà jẹ́ gíláàsì, ṣùgbọ́n àwọn wọ̀nyí ń wo àwọn ọgbà àjàrà, kọ́ńtà igi tó tóbi tí wọ́n gbé sórí wọn kí àwọn ènìyàn lè wo ìwọ̀ oòrùn nígbà tí wọ́n bá ń mu. Wọ́n ṣètò àwọn òkè gíga ní àárín yàrá náà, àti nínú ògiri fèrèsé ní òdìkejì ilé-ọtí náà, ilé-ìdáná ńlá kan dé ọ̀nà àjà gíga, iná ń fọ́ tí ó sì fò nínú rẹ̀.
tn: Ke monko o o tukang wa kedare o o tukang mo go rona fa re tsena mo kamoreng e e sa boneng. Ntlo e e borethe ya segompieno e tsamaya mo leboteng la molema, lebota le le neng le le mo morago ga lone le ne le goga ka botlalo, di-casks tse dikgolo tsa beine di ne tsa opa morago mme di phatsima ka bonolo mo leseding la gouta. Marako a mang a mang a mararo a tshwana le a galase, empa a sheba hodima masimo a merara, e leng ditsere tse tshesane tsa dikgong, hore batho ba tle ba bone letsatsi le dintshi ha di ntse di eja. Marulelo a a kwa godimo a rulagantswe mo gare ga kamore, mme mo leboteng le le fasetereng le lebaganye le bar, molelo o mogolo o fitlha kwa siling e e besitsweng, molelo o o gagabanyang le go tlola mo teng ga ona.

Ua faanahohia te mau hi'opo'araa teitei i ropu i te piha, e i roto i te papa'i haamaramarama i piha'i iho i te fare inuraa, te vai ra te hoê vahi tahuraa auahi rahi i ni'a i te aroaro fare, te ama ra te auahi e te ou'a ra i roto.
mai: मद्धिम रोशनी वला कोठरीमे प्रवेश करैत काल जरैत देवदार जकाँ गंध हमरासभ दिस आबि जाइत अछि। बाम दीवारक कातमे एकटा चिकना आधुनिक पट्टी चलैत अछि, एकर पाछूक दीवार पूर्ण रूपसँ धूम्रपान कयल गेल काँच, एकर पाछाँ पैघ शराबक कास्क ठाढ़ अछि आ धीरे-धीरे सुनहरा प्रकाशमे चमकैत अछि। आन तीनटा देवाल सेहो काँच अछि, मुदा ई दाखक बगान पर देखैत अछि, ओकर कातमे लकड़ीक एकटा संकीर्ण काउंटर लागल अछि जाहिसँ लोक घूँट खाइत सूर्यास्त देख सकथि। कमराक बीचमे ऊँच शीर्षक व्यवस्था कयल गेल अछि, आ बारक सामने खिड़कीवला देवालमे, एकटा विशाल स्लेट फायरप्लेस तिजोरीवला छत दिस पहुँचैत अछि, लपट चटकैत आ ओकर भीतर छलांग मारैत अछि।

en: We fall back into step. The earth goes sandy as we climb. The trees thin, until suddenly we reach the crest and we’re overlooking the steep slope of a dune. At its foot, the dark lake rolls in on the sand, and across the expanse of beach, several bonfires blaze in the dark, several tents ringed around the most distant.
st: Re khutlela mohatong oa pele. Lefatše le ea lehlabathe ha re ntse re nyoloha. Ho fihlela ka tšohanyetso re fihla sebakeng sa rona sa marang-rang' me ka tšohanyetso re ntse re e-na le lekhalo le leholo. Ka maoto a eona, letša le lefifi le ntse le le lehlabatheng, 'me ka mose ho fetisisa lebopong la leoatle, li-bonfires tse' maloa li tuka lefifing, litente tse 'maloa li ne li lesale ho potoloha se hole haholo.
yo: A padà sí ìgbésẹ̀. Ilẹ̀ ń lọ ní iyanrìn bí a bá gun òkè. Àwọn igi náà fẹ́rẹ̀ẹ́ fẹ́rẹ̀ẹ́ fẹ́ Ní ẹsẹ̀ rẹ̀, adágún dúdú náà wọlé lórí iyanrìn, àti kọjá etí òkun, ọ̀pọ̀lọpọ̀ iná iná jó nínú òkùnkùn, ọ̀pọ̀lọpọ̀ àgọ́ ló dún yíká ibi tó jìnnà jù.
tn: Re boela kwa kgatong ya rona. The Earth Goes Sandy As We Go Ka ponyo ya leitlho, go fitlha ka tshoganyetso, re ne ra leba kwa tlase ga lesoka le le omeletseng. Mo godimo ga moo, letsha le le lefifi le ne le dikologa mo letshitshing la lewatle, mme go kgabaganya motshitshi wa lewatle, go na le di-bonfires tse dintsintsi mo lefifing, ditente di le mmalwa di ne di leletsa go dikologa sekgala se se kwa kgakala.

en: There was a time when I was okay at making friends. But that was probably four or five relocations back. Eventually, it didn’t seem worth it anymore, cracking myself open to let someone in, only to have them violently extracted months later when Mom got transferred again.

en: (When they got to his house after dinner, he made her sit with him in the car for twenty unspeaking minutes while the Phish album he’d put on finished playing, then did the exact same thing after he drove her home.)
st: (Ha ba fihla ntlong ea hae kamora ho ja lijo tsa mantsiboea, o ile a lula le eena ka koloing metsotso e mashome a mabeli e sa bonahaleng ha album ea Phish eo a neng a e kentse e felile, joale e ntan'o etsa ntho e tšoanang ka mor'a hore a khanna hae.)

en: I cast my mind back, to before grad school, before undergrad even, all the way to the first moment I remember loving a story. Feeling like I was living it. Being, even as a child, bowled over by how something imaginary could become real, could wring every emotion from me or make me homesick for places I’d never been.

en: Instead my hands scrape up his arms. They feel amazing. Not gym arms, just arms that get a fair amount of daily use. For such a scruffy man, his skin is smooth, the hairs on his forearms fine and soft. My fingers instinctively follow the ridges of his veins up to his biceps, the anchor tattoo on one and the old-school bird on the other. I follow the curve of his shoulders, carried by an unstoppable current.

Bakeng sa monna ea joalo ea scruffy, letlalo la hae le boreleli, moriri o ka forearms ea hae o motle ebile o bonolo. Menoana ea ka ka tlhaho e latela likhaba tsa methapo ea hae ho fihlela li-biceps tsa hae, tattoo ea ankora ho e 'ngoe le nonyana ea sekolo sa khale ho e' ngoe. yo: Kàkà bẹ́ẹ̀ ọwọ́ mi máa ń kó apá rẹ̀ sókè. Wọ́n ní ìmọ̀lára ìyanu. Kì í ṣe apá eré ìdárayá, àwọn apá nìkan ni wọ́n máa ń rí iye ìlò ojoojúmọ́. en: Then I get in bed and try to read, without any success. Then I try to watch an action movie and quickly realize it’s not fun to watch that sort of thing alone, so I take to scrolling social media, seeing college friends’ summer pregnancy announcements, a Richmond coworker’s recent trip to Thailand to see family, and then, without any warning, there she is, on my screen.

en: I’d assumed we’d be boating on Lake Michigan, but there are dozens of smaller lakes further inland from the twenty-two-thousand square miles of Lake Michigan. We’re going to one of those, a lake in the more traditional sense of the word, with rustic cottages lining the water and reeds swaying in the shallows.

Re ea ho e 'ngoe ea tsona, letša ka kutloisiso ea setso ea lentsoe, ka li-cottages rustic linings metsi le ho sisinyeha ka hare ho sa tebang.

en: We move slowly, heavily, and every time one of us reaches a tipping point, we turn. Rearrange. Find new ways to hold each other, to move together. Lying on our sides, him behind me, his arm draped over my hip and his hand tucked between my thighs, he murmurs my name, like it’s an exclamation, the sound you make after a perfect sip of wine.

en: The chair scrapes back. I turn to find him marching toward me. I still have an ivory table runner gripped in my hands when he grabs them and holds them between us. “I’m so sorry,” he says. “I was stupid and shortsighted. It was all just about chasing a rush, and honestly . . . I think I was afraid of the commitment. Of marriage.”

en: “I was just so scared I couldn’t really do it on my own,” she goes on. “And so many decisions I made were based on the fear of what could go wrong, instead of my hopes for what might go right.
